    Does the pursuit of scientific excellence serve or hamper translational medical research: an historical perspective from hematological malignancies.
We then discuss the history of arsenic trioxide as additional APL therapy, and the repurposing of thalidomide as effective multiple myeloma therapy. These stories have surprising elements of commonality that demand debate about the modern-day hard and soft governance of medical research and whether these processes appropriately align the priorities of advancing scientific knowledge and the need of patients.
